{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"e5f687cd-f398-4401-8b26-1c30e6db1c3d","content":"## What happened\n\n**Apple's Security framework does not implement DSA**, and .NET on macOS relies on it for cryptographic primitives. In .NET 10 a managed/OpenSSL-based fallback still existed, but **.NET 11 removed that fallback**, so `DSA.Create()` now throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on macOS.\n\nDSA has been marked `[Obsolete]` (diagnostic `SYSLIB0028`) since .NET 7, signaling this removal.\n\n## How to fix it\n\nSince you only need **verification of legacy signatures** (not new signing), you have two practical options:\n\n### Option 1 — Use BouncyCastle (recommended, pure managed code)\n\n```bash\ndotnet add package BouncyCastle.Cryptography\n```\n\n```csharp\nusing Org.BouncyCastle.Crypto.Parameters;\nusing Org.BouncyCastle.Security;\n\n// Verify a legacy DSA signature with BouncyCastle (works on all platforms)\nbool VerifyDsa(byte[] publicKeyDer, byte[] message, byte[] signature)\n{\n    var keyParam = (DsaPublicKeyParameters)PublicKeyFactory.CreateKey(publicKeyDer);\n    var verifier = SignerUtilities.GetSigner(\"SHA-1withDSA\");\n    verifier.Init(forSigning: false, keyParam);\n    verifier.BlockUpdate(message, 0, message.Length);\n    return verifier.VerifySignature(signature);\n}\n```\n\nThis is cross-platform (Linux, Windows, macOS) with no native dependencies.\n\n### Option 2 — Platform-conditional code using `DSAOpenSsl`\n\nIf OpenSSL is installed on the macOS machine (e.g. via Homebrew), you can use `DSAOpenSsl` directly:\n\n```csharp\nusing System.Security.Cryptography;\nusing System.Runtime.InteropServices;\n\nDSA CreateDsa()\n{\n    if (RuntimeInformation.IsOSPlatform(OSPlatform.OSX))\n        return new DSAOpenSsl(); // requires OpenSSL on macOS\n    return DSA.Create();         // native on Linux/Windows\n}\n```\n\n> **Recommendation:** Go with **Option 1** (BouncyCastle). It has zero native dependencies, works identically on all three platforms, and avoids the fragility of relying on a deprecated API that will eventually be removed everywhere. Plan a migration from DSA to **ECDSA** or **Ed25519** for any new signing workflows.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"339d49fd-b8e8-4829-babf-b62b35167651","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET compatibility issue with DSA (Digital Signature Algorithm) on macOS after upgrading from .NET 10 to .NET 11. Let me reason through this based on my knowledge of .NET's evolution and Apple's security framework changes.\n\nThis is a knowledge question about .NET platform changes, not a codebase task. Let me answer directly.\n\nThe key issue: Apple has been deprecating older cryptographic algorithms in their security frameworks. Starting with macOS, Apple removed support for DSA from their CommonCrypto/Security framework. .NET on macOS uses Apple's native crypto libraries (via the Security.framework / CommonCrypto), and when Apple drops support for DSA, .NET's `DSA.Create()` throws a `PlatformNotSupportedException` on macOS.\n\n\n.NET itself has also been phasing out DSA as a legacy algorithm—it was already marked obsolete with warnings in earlier versions, and newer releases are removing it entirely or restricting it on platforms where the underlying OS no longer supports it. Wait, but the user said it worked on .NET 10, so maybe there was a managed implementation or OpenSSL fallback that got removed in .NET 11. Let me think through what actually changed between versions on macOS—it could be that .NET 11 dropped support for a fallback mechanism that was previously available. DSA has actually been throwing `PlatformNotSupportedException` on macOS since .NET 5 or 6, so .NET 11 likely just completed the removal of whatever OpenSSL fallback was still available. To work around this, I could try using `DSAOpenSsl` directly if it's still exposed, or better yet, migrate to ECDSA or RSA since DSA is obsolete anyway.\n\nFor cases where I need to verify existing DSA signatures, I can pull in BouncyCastle through the Portable.BouncyCastle NuGet package, which has its own managed DSA implementation that works cross-platform. I could also add runtime checks to pick the right implementation based on the platform.","outputTokens":1845,"requestId":"6C35:3EB10:1922A80:1CA9C71:69FE92B5"},"id":"3f149783-5b7e-413b-adb7-d4195d4d00be","timestamp":"2026-05-09T01:50:19.346Z","parentId":"1488cf10-88ec-4f68-b287-186e424feefd"}
